On August 1, 2019, at 0737 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics UKC regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a loose cap, approximately 8 ounces of Multi-Chlor Bleach (Hypochlorite solution, UN1791) was released from (1) 50-gallon poly drum; the released product was contained to the top of the tote.  Terminal personnel cleaned up the release with a couple of shop towels and the proper PPE. The terminal loosened the cap, re-tightened it, and performed a slosh test before shipping it on to the consignee. ERTS then advised terminal personnel to take the shop rags they used for clean up, wet them with water, and dispose of them in the garbage as household trash.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, PALED AND PLACED ON THE UPPER BELT FEEDING THE DOGHOUSE. THE PACKAGE THEN SLID DOWN A 10 FOOT CHUTE. THE PRE-LOADER NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS WET AND HE COULD SMELL A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM IT. HE STOPPED THE BELT, LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THAN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER, FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, PLACED THE PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TUB. THE EQUIPMENT WAS DECONTAMINATED FOLLOWING THE DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST. THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. IT WAS THERE THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE UNDECLARED.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: On 08/02/2019 0425 hrs. CSX personnel advised that TILX 135477 and WAGX 3056 both loads of Molten Sulphur, arrived in the CSX Rougemere Yard Dearborn MI with product coming from what appeared to be the manway covers. Upon the arrival of CSX contractor Hepaco, it was found that TILX 135477 had a blown rupture disc and was releasing approximately 3 gallons product through the vent tube. WAGX 3056 had approximately 1 gallon of product releasing from the manway cover which was not secure and had one of six manway bolts laying down. WAGX 3056 also had a misaligned and damaged nozzle gasket.  At 0730 hrs. GATX 60250 was also observed to a have a blown rupture disc and releasing approximately ½ gallon of product from the vent tube. All product was contained and adhered to the top of the cars with no release to the ground or exposure. Hepaco cleaned all residue off of all cars and replaced the damaged rupture discs and manway nozzle gasket, while securing all fittings.

On 08/05/2019, UPGZ 512745 was reported leaking a white substance upon deramp at BNSF San Bernardino IMF. This unit was billed as carrying hazardous material. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit pending interior inspection.  Hazmat One was contacted and subsequently sent Ocean Blue to remediate the load. Interior inspection mixed load of freight, stowed 2 wide and 2 high with no doorway securement. The origin of the leak was two 5 gallon totes of Chem Aqua (Hazardous) at the rear of the trailer. These 2 tote were cracked when a pallet of forklift forks fell from the second layer. Both of the totes were completely empty with approximately 2 gallons reaching the ground.
column169: Shipper to review BNSF Policies on Intermodal Loading, Blocking and Bracing.

ON THURSDAY, 1 AUGUST 19', JCI BARBERTON'S DRIVER WAS AT THE EAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO WATER TREATMENT PLANT MAKING A TANKER DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. CLOSE TO THE END OF THE TANKER UNLOADING PROCESS AND JUST PRIOR TO THE DRIVER 'BLOWING CLEAR' THE UNLOADING HOSE OF RESIDUAL SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WITH AIR, THE CUSTOMER'S 2" PVC QUICK DISCONNECT BETWEEN THEIR HOOKUP POINT AND JCI'S UNLOADING HOSE FAILED, RELEASING SOMETHING LESS THAN 20 GALLONS ONTO THE GROUND (CONCRETE). JCI'S DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE AIR VALVE ON THE TANKER AS WELL AS THE BALL VALVE IN THE CUSTOMER'S HOOKUP POINT ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING IN WHICH THE STORAGE TANKS ARE LOCATED AND THE CUSTOMER'S OPERATORS CLOSED THE VALVE IN THE TRANSFER LINE LEADING TO THE STORAGE TANKS INSIDE THE BUILDING. AS A RESULT OF THIS, THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED OVER THE COURSE OF LESS THAN FIVE SECONDS WAS PRIMARILY LIMITED TO THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT IN THE HOSE AT THE TIME THE QUICK DISCONNECT FAILED AND EVEN SMALLER AMOUNT FROM THE HOOKUP POINT PIPING.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THIS RELEASE WAS DUE SOLEY TO THE FAILURE OF THE 2" QUICK DISCONNECT IN THE CUSTOMER'S HOOKUP SYSTEM USED TO OFFLOAD TANKERS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE; I.E, WHERE THE SUPPLIER'S (JCI'S) HOSE IS CONNECTED FOR UNLOADING THE PRODUCT. BASED ON CONVERSATIONS WITH THE FACILITY'S CHIEF OPERATOR, IT IS BELIEVED THAT BOTH AGE AND EXPOSURE TO THE ELEMENTS WERE LIKELY THE LEADING FACTORS CONTRIBUTING TO THIS FAILURE.

column168: Our cargo tank left our storage yard facility located at 2804 S County Rd 1242, Midland, TX 79706 and proceeded to travel west on industrial ave.  Workers from TXDOT noticed that the tank was leaking product, so they proceeded to follow and flag down our unit.  The cargo tank came to a stop on the access or frontage road to access South Loop 250, Midland TX 79703.  Midland PD, Midland FD and TCEQ were notified and responded to the scene.  TCEQ confirmed the leakage was minimal and that soda ash could be used to neutralize whatever acid was spilled on the roadway.  The cargo tank was leaking from the front manhole cover assembly, technicians discovered that the manhole assembly was faulty and as a result the cause of the leak.  The cargo tank was then equalized with the rear compartment, since the rear compartment was empty.  This allowed the product level to go down enough to prevent leakage.  The cargo tank was then driven and escorted back to the loading yard for unloading and repairs.  From the time of stop to the time the situation was resolved, there was about an hour duration where the road had to be closed to the motoring public.
column169: We will implement additional safety measure practices in order to prevent future leakages.  Drivers will be trained to stop before leaving a loading facility and do a walk around check of valves, closures, manholes, pressure relief devices to ensure no product is leaking.  Loaders will also be retrained to check for deficiencies and faults on all cargo tank vehicles.

Due to the terminal not having the materials needed to clean the spill and not knowing if the battery itself is damaged, ERTS dispatched contractors to contain and clean the release. At 0801 EST, contractors arrived on site.  Contractors confirmed the release impacted a 2' x 2' area of the dock floor. Bicarbonate ash was utilized to neutralize release which was then swept up and put into a 35 gallon poly drum. The battery was decontaminated for shipment on to the consignee. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On August 14, 2019, at 1546 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal LDA regarding a cargo release. column168: On August 7, 2019, at 0055 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal NAT regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a failed bung cap, (1) 55-gallon metal drum of Glacial Acetic Acid (UN2789) releasing approximately 3 ounces of product contained to the top of the drum.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The bung cap on the top of the drum was replaced and the drum was forwarded to the consignee.  The contractor generated (1) 5-gallon plastic pail of waste which included damaged bung cap, spent absorbents and all other debris.  The waste pail was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 55-gallon metal drum of Urethane Reducer Medium (Paint related material, flammable, UN1263) was punctured, releasing approximately 15 gallons of product on to a 25' x 4' area of the trailer floor. On August 14, 2019, at 1143 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal UEO regarding a cargo release. The 30 gallon fiber drum arrived at Veolia's 10-day transfer facility in Schenectady, NY in good condition.  A Veolia employee removed the 30 gallon fiber drum from the truck and placed it on the warehouse floor while they were finalizing the shipment count.  When the Veolia employee went back to the 30 gallon fiber drum they noticed that the bottom of the container was saturated from a  broken inner container that leaked.  The estimated amount of spilled material inside the 30 gallon fiber drum was estimated to be about 1 gallon.  There was absorbent (vermiculite) inside of the drum so the leak did not go beyond the outside of the 30 gallon fiber drum.  The 30 gallon fiber drum was  overpacked and shipped to its final destination.  It was determined that the 30 gallon fiber drum might not have had enough absorbent material to cushion the inner containers which resulted in an inner container breaking.
column169: To help mitigate this from occurring again Veolia EHS Managers discussed the spill incident with the  Veolia field technicians during the weekly safety training on 8/21/19.  The training included steps to ensure that all packages contain an adequate amount of absorbent material to cushion the inner  containers.

column168: On August 23, 2019, at 0330 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal LSL regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 55-gallon metal drum of Polyshield Hi-E Elastomeric Polyurea (Amines, liquid, corrosive, n.o.s., UN2735) was punctured, releasing approximately 2 gallons of product on to a 3' x 3' area of the dock floor.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 85-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: On August 23, 2019, at 0734 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal NRG regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to overpressurization, (2) 55-gallon poly drums of Acetic Acid, UN2789 released approximately 3 ounces of product; the release was contained to the top of the drums.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The release was cleaned up and all waste generated was containerized in (1) 30-gallon poly drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.  The drums were inspected to ensure to visible damage and were then forwarded on to the consignee.

On August 23, 2019, at 1025 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XLA regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, (1) 1-gallon plastic jug of Defy Exterior Wood Stain Stripper (Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., UN3266) was damaged, releasing approximately 6 ounces of product inside a trailer.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. The impacted freight, spent absorbents and other debris were containerized in (1) 8-gallon poly lined drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged container, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1330 hrs. on 8-25-2019, while the Brewster Yard Train Crew was switch a cut of cars that this asphalt car was in, they noticed Asphalt leaking from the top of the car GLNX 23764.  They notified the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer for the WLE Railway. I came out to inspect the car and had found that Asphalt was leaking form the manway lid that was partially open about a half and inch.  All the swing bolts were in place and tight. I removed the old seal which I was not able to read the number of since it was covered in Asphalt.  I investigated before I opened the lid and found that the reason the lid did not close all the way was because the lid was stuck on the safety collars of the swing bolts not allowing the lid to close all the way.  I opened the lid all the way to check the lid gasket and found that it should be replaced.  I replaced the gasket with a new one.  I then adjusted the safety collars on the bolts and closed the lid and tightened the bolts.  Installed new seal number 971762 and then had the car sent over to the car shop tracks so that I could arrange to have the car cleaned before it was released.
column169: Better car securement inspections need followed.

column168: At 0200 hrs.on 8/12/2019, I was called by the Brewster Yardmaster about tank car UTLX 213062 in Brewster yard that the car inspector said he could small a petroleum, odor from.  The car was in 29 track.  When I arrived, I found that there was product leaking form the bottom outlet valve and that the valve nozzle was wet.  The cap was tight.  The valve handle was closed.  I loosened the cap to see how much product would come out and after the initial gush of fluid, the leak drained down to a drip.  I took the cap the rest of the way off and looked up inside the valve and noticed that the seal around the ball was leaking through.  I put the cap back on and tightened it with a 36” pipe wrench.  The leak stopped.  I had the car set to the car shop tracks to eventually be transloaded.  This car was tranloaded by Enviroserve on 8/15/2019 and home shop stickers were applied.  Markwest with apply for a movement approval to move to their facility for final repairs.  NARRI: 2(5+5)x2+0=40                                                      Cause Codes: Ball Valve Seat Failed - Could not find a code for this
column169: This defect may not have been able to be noticed during an inspection.

column168: The tank car was reported to be leaking by UPRR yard personnel in the Settegast Yard in Houston Texas. Manager of Hazardous Materials Tom Robinson was called to plan a response. The tank car was inspected and observed to have leaked from the man way. The man way swing bolts were found to be less than wrench tight and the gasket was deteriorated enough to not make a good seal on the man way rim nozzle. The gasket was replaced and the tank car properly sealed. No further remediation was required.
column169: Manager Robinson discussed the cause of the release with the shipper Kinder Morgan. Kinder Morgan stated they would investigate the car loading process and retrain their employees on proper tank car securement.

The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd via the rail from Dallas, TX to Long Beach, CA to be loaded on the BROTONNE Bridge 930S to Sydney, Australia as non-hazardous cargo.  The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the container load on the rail from Dallas and arrived in Long Beach of undeclared hazardous material loaded in the container.  The shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials.  The shipper subsequently provided hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd and sailed on the vessel as hazardous materials.
column169: Shipper was placed on notice and fined as per tariff of the Undeclared hazardous materials via the rail.

column168: RESPONDED TO LEAKER IN TRAILER

On August 6, 2019 at 0900 EST, ESTES experienced a one (1) - gallon release of UN1789, Hydrochloric acid, 8, PGII "Muriatic Acid" from a one (1) - gallon plastic jug inside of a fiberboard box due to improper loading. It was reported that the release impacted the dock floor at their terminal. ESTES notified Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) of the release at 0940 EST. ERTS dispatched Hepaco at 1103 EST who confirmed an ETA of 1130 EST. At 1123 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately one gallon of product released to a 6'x3' area of the dock floor as well as the pallet the boxes were stacked on. Personnel also advised that seven other bottles were impacted from the release and were disposed of. The impacted dock floor was neutralized and solidified with granular absorbents. The impacted bottles, pallet, cardboard, spent absorbents and other debris were containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly waste drums. At 1329 EST, Hepaco personnel departed site and left the waste at the terminal for ESTES to manage.

column168: DIVERSIFIED ENERGY MONITORS THE TANK LEVELS FOR WASTE MANAGEMENT. DIVERSIFIED ENERGY DISPATCH SENT US A LOAD FOR 4,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL TO WASTE MANAGEMENT SITE IN ST. CLOUD, MN. WAYNE TRANSPORTS DRIVER LOADED 4,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FOR ST. CLOUD AND 3,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FOR ANOTHER LOCATION. DRIVER ARRIVED AND ABOVE GROUND TANK LEVEL READ 5'4". WASTE MANAGEMENT DID NOT HAVE A TANK CHART FOR DRIVER. SINCE DIVERSIFIED ENERGY MONITORS THE TANKS OUR DRIVER UNLOADED. ABOUT 3/4 DONE UNLOADING PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT VENT PIPES. BLUE ABSORBENT PADS AND GRANULAR ABSORBENT WAS PUT DOWN. RELEASE OF PRODUCT LASTED FOR 20-30 SECONDS.
column169: TWO RECOMMENDATIONS:  1. CALIBRATE OR TEST THE ACCURACY OF THE TANK MONITOR EQUIPMENT.  2. HAVE A TANK CHART ATTACHED TO THE TANK SO A DRIVER CAN USE THE MEASUREMENT AND TANK CHART TO CONFIRM IF THE PRODUCT WILL FIT. THE DRIVER WOULD THEN NOT HAVE TO WORRY IF THE AMOUNT ORDERED WOULD FIT.

column168: On August 28, 2019, at 0616 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XSW regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a load shift in transit, (1) 1-gallon metal can of Epoxy Reducer Medium Slow (Paint, flammable, UN1263) was damaged, releasing approximately 1 quart of product on to the trailer floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged metal can, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 5-gallon poly drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On August 29, 2019, at 1040 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XKO regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a loose cap, (1) 270-gallon poly tote of : UNI-KLEEN LIQUID ALUM SAFE (Potassium hydroxide, solution, UN1814) released approximately 3 cups of product on to a 2' x 2' area of the trailer floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The cap was tightened and a slosh test was performed to ensure the tote was secure, and the release was then cleaned up.  The spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (1) 5-gallon poly pail which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On August 29, 2019, at 1201 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XIN. It was reported that (1) 100-gallon metal tote of THERMOSET ES-73 RESIN (Environmentally hazardous substances, liquid, n.o.s., UN3082) released approximately 1 pint of product on to the trailer floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. It was also reported that the tote was still intact and the release was due to a possible loose cap.  It was undetermined as the tote had already be delivered to the consignee upon discovery of the release.  The spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 30-gallon poly drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

At 1235 EST, XPO XIN contacted ERTS to report a 5 to 10-gallon release of a UN1866 Resin Solution (HAP33 Ice White) from a 55-gallon drum to an 8'x5' area of the trailer floor. The cause of the release is unknown and the terminal reports that it arrived this way. Due to the size of the release and the terminal indicating a strong odor, ERTS will dispatch a contractor to clean the release. No drains or waterways were impacted by this release and all waste was properly contained and left at the terminal OS&D for terminal employees to manage.

column168: THERE WERE TWO 2.5L BOTTLES IN THE SHIPMENT. CLOSURES ON THE BOTTLES FAILED, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ON OUTER CARTON, BOTH CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE PRELOAD SUPERVISOR IN TROY/EXTENDED. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED THE DISTRICT SPILL COORDINATOR (MIKE LUEKER). THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER VENDOR (ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATIONS) WAS CONTACTED: THEIR RESPONDER ARRIVED WITHIN AN HOUR AND CONTAINED THE DAMAGE (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED IT TO THE EARTH CITY DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION BY A UPS RESPONDER (MAS) REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 (1-GAL) PLASTIC JUGS WAS LOOSE BY APPROX. 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING THE LIQUID PRODUCT TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLE WALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT 350 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.
DECLARED LEAKING HAZMAT DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.
WENT TO PACKAGE CAR DONNED PPE CLEANED UP SPILL AND CONTAINERIZED LEAKER RETURNED TO SC FOR DISPOSAL

column168: On August 30, 2019, at 0740 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal LTX regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a load shift in transit, (1) 5-gallon metal pail of Polybond Liquid Adhesive (Coating solution, UN1139) was crushed, releasing approximately 5 gallons of product on to the trailer floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged pail, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 10-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On August 30, 2019, at 2125 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XML regarding a cargo release. column168: THE HAZ-MAT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING ON THE HUB SECONDARY SLIDE OF THE EARTH CITY, MO UPS HUB AT 19:00. THE PACKAGE (A SINGLE WALL, 12X12X12 INCH, 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST, FIBERBOARD BOX) WAS ON ITS SIDE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID. THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED, CONTAINED, AND ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. AN EXTERNAL INSPECTION SHOWED NO DIRECT SIGNS OF DAMAGE FROM THE SHIPPING PROCESS. AN INTERNAL INSPECTION REVEALED NO PACKING MATERIAL BETWEEN THE INNER RECEPTACLES (4, 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES) AND THE OUTER WALL OF THE CARTON. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILLAGE WAS A COMBINATION OF THE HAZ-MAT BEING ON ITS SIDE AND A LOOSE CAP. ALL MATERIAL HAS BEEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM.

column168: LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE CALLED IN. PICKED UP BY RESPONDER, TRANSPORTED TO THE HAZMAT AREA AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP. CAP WAS LOOSE AND LEAKING.

THE DOOR OF TRAILER 876058 FROM NORTH BAY WAS OPENED BY SUPV JOHN LYNCH, WHO NOTICED A DAMP HAZ MAT BOX LAYING ON ITS SIDE AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. HE NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER DAVID BRAND, WHO DONNED HIS PPE AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE TO RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE. OUTER PACKAGE WAS DAMP, INNER PACKING HAD A PLASTIC BAG THAT WAS ZIP TIED AND ABSORBENT PADDING WHICH CONTAINED THE MAJORITY OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL. IT WAS A UN SPEC BOX. THE CAP WAS LOOSE.

column168: AT 0935 ON 11 AUG 2019,  KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) PERSONNEL WORKING IN THE KCS SHREVEPORT, LA RAIL YARD REPORTED AN ODOR. KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE.  UPON ARRIVAL, RESIDUE TANK CAR SHPX 221863 (ANHYDROUS AMMONIA) WAS DISCOVERED WITH A FAINT AMMONIA ODOR AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. RESPONDERS OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND DISCOVERED THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT, AND THE A END LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT. ALSO THE VAPOR LINE PLUG WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT. RESPONDERS SECURED THE LIQUID LINE VALVE BY CLOSING IT 1/2 ROTATION. THE LOOSE LIQUID LINE AND VAPOR LINE PLUGS WERE REMOVED, TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED, AND THE PLUGS WERE REINSTATED INTO THE VALVES TOOL TIGHT. ONCE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SECURED, THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NAR ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: 08/22/19, at 11:59 hours, A FRA inspector in the PANAM Yard Rotterdam NY discovered MTZX330076, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and AUX SABLE Liquid Products LP, Schenectady Hazmat team, Rotterdam Junction NYS DEC and NRC were notified.  (CHEMTREC 2019082200212. CSX Hazmat Manager D. Scoons, Responded to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon claiming the railcar and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the liquid line valve was open and the secondary securement plug was uninstalled but not tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Brad Brancato 1-815-715-0642. H/M Scoons closed the liquid line valve and tightened the secondary plug. The leak was secured and the car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

FRTL driver was making a left turn onto Highway 74 and due to excessive speed the tractor trailer overturned onto it's right side.  The fire department identified an intermittent drip of product coming from a securement cap on the dome.  The fire department captured the drip in a five gallon bucket preventing release into the environment.  Our emergency response contractor, Hepaco performed an environmental assessment of the area after the tractor trailer had been removed for the scene.  Hepaco no further action was needed to address any environmental issue.    This report is being filed for informational purposes only.

column168: Driver descended Douglas Pass and was not using the brakes or gears correctly which caused his speed to be too high while going into a 15 MPH corner. The driver failed to negotiate the curve; the trailer tipped over onto it's side and took the truck over with it onto the side of the roadway. The accident caused the trailer to leak about a gallon of crude oil every ten minutes for one hour for a total of 60 gallons lost. Colorado State Patrol, fire and ambulance responded, as well as Basin Western dispatch and safety team. Basin Western initiated calls with their insurance agency. Great West Casualty, to involve them in the emergency response. Another Basin Western Truck and trailer responded to help drill a hole into the side of the trailer and pump off the crude oil and delivered it to the original destination in Rangely. A tow truck took the damaged truck and trailer to Basin Western's yard in Grand Junction. LMH Environmental was assigned to work on environmental remediation and they hired STII Environmental to help. Road closure was necessary while the truck and trailer were towed and during the clean-up  process. As of August 27th, 2019, the excavation had been completed and STII put in groundwater monitoring wells to asses any groundwater impact.
column169: Basin Western Management and Safety Compliance Teams held an Accident Review  with the driver to determine root cause and corrective actions. The driver was not using the brakes or gears correctly and this caused a failure to negotiate the curve. The driver was cited for careless driving and is currently out on  leave with Worker's Comp. When the driver is released to return to they will be subject to an Accountability Action Review to determine any further disciplinary action. We are focusing safety measures on drivers taking the time to familiarize themselves with the equipment they are using, be aware of their surroundings, and abide by our speeding policy and use caution when descending a mountain pass.

column168: Driver was unloading Sodium Hydroxide at Sensient Flavors, after he got his bills signed a Sensient employee verified the emergency overflow alarm was working. Once they verified the alarm was working the driver began unloading. During the unloading process the emergency alarm failed and the tank was overfilled. Approximately 20 gallons of product overflowed into the secondary containment and 1 gallon out of containment. After further investigation the bolts were missing around the caustic pump flange which allowed product to splash out when air was fed inside of the storage tank during the truck's blowdown of the caustic feed hose/line. This caused product to splash out of the tank.
column169: The sensient plant has installed a temporary fix to seal the opening while they wait to receive in a new manway cover and pump assembly that correctly mates to the tank.

On August 14, 2019, Roadrunner Transportation experienced a 15 - gallon release of UN1247, Methyl methacrylate monomer, stabilized, 3, PGII "Caresse Monomer" from several 1 - gallon plastic jugs in boxes that experienced a load shift in transit due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to perform emergency response and cleanup acivities. At 1228 ET, the contractor arrived onsite and advised that (23) 1 - gallon poly jugs were damaged from the load shift and approximately 15 - gallons of product released onto the asphalt when terminal personnel were unloading the pallets. The product that released inside of the trailer had evaporated. The contractor decontaminated the impacted asphalt and containerized the 23 jugs into one (1) 55-gallon poly waste drum. The spent absorbents and debris were placed into an additional 55-gallon poly waste drum. The contractor staged the waste drums on site until a profile could be completed.

AT 2200 ON 8/26/19, A UPS RESPONDER RECEIVED A CALL THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE THAT WAS WARM TO THE TOUCH. UPON ARRIVAL HE INSPECTED THE OUTER MARKINGS TO SEE IF THE PACKAGE WAS HAZARDOUS, BUT THE ONLY MARKINGS WERE A "FRAGILE" LABEL ON FOUR SIDES OF THE PACKAGE. THE RESPONDER MOVED THE PACKAGE OUTSIDE AND CORDONED OFF THE AREA (15 FEET). AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED AND DISPATCHED TO THE FACILITY. APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES LATER, SMOKE EMANATED FROM THE PACKAGE. THE SMOKE WAS INTERMITTENT WITH FLAMES THAT WOULD GO OUT THEN START UP AGAIN. THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED, EXTINGUISHED THE FLAMES AND DETERMINED THE BOX CONTAINED A FIRE PANEL POWERED BY TWO SEALED LEAD ACID BATTERIES THAT ARCED WHILE IN THE BOX.

column168: A box tore open. Upon inspection of the contents it contained three water filled fire extinguishers. Per the guage it may have discharged some water. A customs and border patrol agent pulled the package from the sort due to concerns that it might contain mercury but conducted no sample tests or inspections. His concerns were assumptions only. However, since the fire extinguishers are under pressure and the shipper had not offered the shipment with any dangerous goods markings, DG labels nor a shipper's declaration, it is thought to be undeclared DG. The FAA was notified via email and photos sent. The package was held for their investigation.

column168: THE DELIVERY COURIER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DELIVERING THE PACKAGE TO THE COSIGNEE. THE EMPLOYEE WAS HOLDING THE PACKAGE AGAINST THEIR HIP WHEN THEY NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING AND A SMALL AMOUNT DRIPPED ON THEIR LEG. THE COSIGNEE TOOK POSSESSION OF THE SHIPMENT SO WE DO NOT HAVE COMPLETE DETAILS ON THE INNER PACKAGING. THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS A FEDEX COURIER PAK. THE SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR THIS PRODUCT, DESCRIBED ON THE SHIPPER'S DOCUMENTATION AS A SILICONE GEL SAID IT WAS NONHAZARDOUS. HOWEVER, THE EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL. THE EMPLOYEE DID MISS TIME FROM WORK AND WAS ON BED REST AND UNDER THE CARE OF A PHYSICIAN. THE EMPLOYEE'S NAME WAS PRASENJIT BISWAS, EMPLOYEE # 369046. THE PRODUCT CAUSED BLISTERING ON HIS LEG WHERE THE CONTENTS LEAKED. DESPITE THE SDS, WE SUSPECT THIS WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS. THE UN NUMBER, PROPER SHIPPING NAME AND HAZARD CLASS/DIVISION ARE UNKNOWN. I LISTED IT AS A DIVISION 6.1 TOXIC ABOVE AS A PLACEHOLDER. IN ORDER TO DESIGNATE UNDECLARED DG IN OUR SYSTEM WE NEED TO LIST THE UN NUMBER, PROPER SHIPPING NAME AND CLASS/DIVISION NUMBER. ONE OF MY SAFETY COLLEAGUES OVERSEAS WILL NOTIFY THE APPROPRIATE COMPETENT AUTHORITY AS WELL. AS HE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, DG LABELING NOR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION AND DUE TO THE BLISTERING THAT OCCURRED ON THE EMPLOYEE'S LEG FROM COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE MATERIAL, IT'S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DG. NOTE: I SELECTED SORT CENTER AS THE PLACE OF OCCURRENCE BUT OUR SPILL REPORT DOES NOT HAVE A SELECTION FOR ON CUSTOMER'S PROPERTY WHICH IS WHERE THIS SPILL ACTUALLY OCCURRED.

column168: While moving a pallet on the 10 day in-transit facility located at the Veolia facility in Menomonee Falls,  WI, a 10 gallon steel drum fell off of the pallet.  When the drum make contact with the concrete dock, the lid of the drum flew off as a result of pressure from within the drum
column169: Investigation into this incident revealed that the drum, prepared in accordance with DOT-SP 13179, included small refill cylinders of butane in addition to lighters.  The Veolia employee who improperly packed this container believed this to be acceptable as the special permit lists the proper shipping name "Lighters or lighter refills containing flammable gas".  The employee was retrained on the proper  use of the special permit.  Veolia is creating additional training that will be share with all field  employees at every location throughout the company.

column168: On August 12, 2019 at 0845 EST, ESTES experienced a 20-gallon of UN1170, Ethanol, 3, PGII from (1) 265-gallon tote due to being punctured in transit by a pallet that was stacked on top. The release impacted the trailer floor. At 1545 EST, Clean Harbors personnel arrived onsite and advised that the released product had evaporated but a tote transfer was necessary as the original tote was compromised. The remaining product was transferred into a new tote. The impacted areas were wiped down and all cleanup debris was placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was left onsite to dispose of.

column168: Landstar Ranger Cargo- experienced a release of CE330 Epoxy Binder Part B from a Poly Tote to the trailer floor, as a result of a Cargo Shift while in Transit.   Contractor arrived on site and has determined that the leak was caused due to lose caps on the totes.  Contractor has tightened all the caps on the totes as well as checked other totes that were not affected to ensure all are secured. The contractor has cleaned up the spill and generated (1) 5 Gallon Poly Drum of impacted absorbents and PPE.  Contractor has taken the Drums off site to be disposed

The Kenan Transport, LLC driver was attempting to deliver diesel fuel into the customers storage tank. In the course of doing so, the connection between the hose adapter and the storage tank became compromised and approximately 15 gallons of diesel fuel was released. The customer dispatched a local environmental contractor to the scene who handled the remediation. No further environmental impact is anticipated.
column169: Kenan Transport, LLC will continue to train and enforce safe loading policies and procedures.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported a strong odor coming from tank car GLNX86365.  Upon inspection by a contractor the odor was the result of a vapor leak from the manway.  The leak was caused by a defective manway gasket.  A new manway gasket was installed and the car was returned to transportation.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING ON NORTH STATE STREET IN CLAIRTON, PENNSYLVANIA WHEN THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL. THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WENT OFF THE ROADWAY AND DOWN AN EMBANKMENT COMING TO A STOP. THE TANK TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 8499 GALLONS OF GASOLINE BUT THERE WAS NO RELEASE. THE ROADWAY WAS SHUT DOWN FOR SEVERAL HOURS AS EMERGENCY PERSONNEL RECOVERED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. A NEARBY RESTAURANT WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES. THE TRUCK AND TANK TRAILER WILL ALSO BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED TO RULE OUT ANY MECHANICAL ISSUES. IF ANY MECHANICAL ISSUES ARE FOUND, THE PROPER REPAIRS WILL BE COMPLETED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: AT 0545 ON 15 AUGUST 2019, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) PERSONNEL WORKING IN THE KANSAS CITY, MO RAIL YARD REPORTED AN ODOR POSSIBLY EMANATING FROM TWO LOADED SULFUR DIOXIDE TANK CARS. KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT RESPONDERS AND RAILROAD QUALIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR MOBILIZED TO THE YARD TO INVESTIGATE.  UPON ARRIVAL, AIR MONITORING AT THE GROUND LEVEL AND ON TOP OF THE TWO SULFUR DIOXIDE TANK CARS INDICATED NON-DETECT LEVELS OF H2S (PPM DETECTION THRESHOLD). FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETECTED MINOR LEAKS AT THE LEFT LIQUID LINE AND PRESSURE RELEASE DEVICE BASE PLATES ON TANK CAR TILX 600998, INDICATED BY A REACTION WITH AMMONIA. RESPONDERS TIGHTENED THE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS AT THE BASE PLATES, STOPPING THE LEAKS.  ONCE SECURE, TILX 600998 WAS NOT RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE SHIPPER APPLIED FOR A OTMA-1 SO THE CAR COULD MOVE TO DESTINATION TO BE OFFLOADED AND THEN TO HOME SHOP TO RE-QUALIFY THE FLANGED CONNECTIONS.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 2019335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.  (NAR: 349, 400)

ATTACHED IS THE ANALYTICAL FOR THE LOAD AS THIS LOAD DOES NOT HAVE AN SDS. ALSO A LETTER WRITTEN TO EPA FROM CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT STATING THAT THE SPILL WAS NOT AN RQ SPILL

column168: On August 27, 2019, at 0042 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XAU experienced a UN 2014, 5.1, 8, pg II Hydrogen Peroxide 35% Durox release from a 55 gallon poly drum due to improper loading. Approximately 2 cups released to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to clean the release as the terminal did not have the materials needed to complete the cleanup. At 0328 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed that due to improper loading, two drums containing Hydrogen Peroxide 35% Durox fell to the trailer floor, causing 2 cups to spill on to an adjacent pallet and on top of the drums. Terminal personnel placed absorbent boom around the drums but by the time the contractors arrived, the release had absorbed and dissolved. The contractor is wiped down the pallet and the drums and will placed the absorbents into a 5-gallon poly drum. The drums were undamaged with no further leakage. All waste was left on site.

On August 29, 2019, at 2124 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XBV notified ERTS of a UN1760 "Kathon CF1400 Biocide" release from a 330 gallon poly tote due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and over packing operations. At 0106 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 165 gallons of product released from the tote. The remaining product was transferred into a new tote. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into (5) 35 gallon poly drums along with all absorbents. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

DURING TRAVEL TO DELIVERY STOP THE BUCKET FELL OVER IN THE BACK OF THE PACKAGE CAR. THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE ANYTHING LEAKING FROM THE BUCKET AND PICKED IT UP BY THE HANDLE TO MAKE DELIVERY. THE SERVICE PROVIDER STATED THAT HE DID NOT NOTICED ANYTHING LEAKING FROM THE BUCKET OR ON THE HANDLE DURING DELIVERY. AT HIS NEXT STOP HE NOTICED THAT PLACES ON HIS HAND WHERE HE HANDLED THE BUCKET WERE BEGINNING TO TURN WHITE AND HE HAD A STINGING SENSATION ON HIS THUMB. AT THIS TIME HE NOTIFIED THE ON ROAD SUPERVISOR FOR THE AREA OF WHAT HE WAS EXPERIENCING. HE STATED THAT HE HAD WASHED HIS HANDS AND THE STINGING WAS NOT GOING AWAY. THE SERVICE PROVIDER WAS TOLD TO STOP WHAT HE WAS DOING AND RETURN TO BUILDING. UPON HIS RETURN HE WAS TAKEN TO RECEIVE MEDICAL TREATMENT.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: FERGUSON ACKNOWLEDGES AN INCIDENT ON AUGUST 22, 2019 INVOLVING A ONE PIECE SHIPMENT TRANSPORTED BY FERGUSON. THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED FOR GROUND SERVICE BY FERGUSON #2623 LOCATED AT 5722 49TH STREET, MASPETH, NJ 11378. THE CONSIGNEE WAS LISTED AS BLACKMAN PLUMBING SUPPLY (A WHOLLY OWNED SUBSIDIARY OF FERGUSON) 900 SYLVAN AVENUE, BAYPORT, NY 11705. THE SHIPMENT SUBSEQUENTLY LEAKED DURING TRANSPORTATION AND AN ASSOCIATE WAS EXPOSED DURING RECEIVING. AFTER INVESTIGATION BY FERGUSON IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED SIX 1 QUART POLYETHYLENE CONTAINERS OF OATEY-HERCULES CLOBBER, IDENTIFIED AS UN1830, SULFURIC ACID, 8, PGII, LIMITED QUANTITY. THE BOTTLES OF ACID WERE NOT PLACED IN STRONG OUTER PACKAGING - THE BOX WAS A REUSED BOX THAT PREVIOUSLY HELD PIPE FITTINGS. THE PACKAGE WAS NOT ORIENTATED CORRECTLY DURING SHIPMENT (BECAUSE IT DID NOT HAVE ORIENTATION ARROWS) WHICH CAUSED ONE OF THE BOTTLES OF SULFURIC ACID TO LEAK AND SUBSEQUENTLY THE ACID DEGRADED THE FIBERBOARD BOX. WHEN THE RECEIVING ASSOCIATE PICKED UP THE BOX HE COULD NOT SEE IT WAS DEGRADED ON THE BOTTOM AND THE BOX FAILED RELEASING LIQUID ACID ON TO HIS CLOTHING AND SKIN. THE ASSOCIATE WAS ALSO UNAWARE THE BOX CONTAINED A LIMITED QUANTITY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BECAUSE THE BOX WAS NOT MARKED. MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED AND WASHED OFF THE ACID, REMOVED IMPACTED CLOTHING AND CALLED THE INTERNAL NURSE LINE SERVICE. THE ASSOCIATE DID NOT REQUIRE FURTHER TREATMENT AND WAS ABLE TO RETURN TO WORK THE NEXT DAY. THE RELEASED SULFURIC ACID WAS CLEANED UP WITH THE SPILL KIT AND DISPOSED OF BY OUR HAZARDOUS WASTE VENDOR, CLEAN HARBORS.
column169: AFTER RECEIVING NOTIFICATION OF THIS INCIDENT BY THE RECEIVING ASSOCIATES AT BLACKMAN, FERGUSON INVESTIGATED THE CIRCUMSTANCES SURROUNDING THIS SHIPMENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THAT ASSOCIATE WHO PACKAGED THE ORDER FAILED TO RECOGNIZE THAT THE PRODUCT REQUIRED SPECIFIC PACKAGING AS WELL AS SPECIFIC LABELING, AND HANDLING MARKINGS. THE ASSOCIATE HAS BEEN SUSPENDED FROM PACKAGING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE AND WILL BE REQUIRED TO UNDERGO EXTENSIVE RE-TRAINING PRIOR TO BEING ALLOWED TO PACKAGE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT. ADDITIONALLY, FERGUSON HAS MODIFIED THE INTERNAL SYSTEM MESSAGE THAT IDENTIFIES HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON THESE SHIPMENTS TO HELP ENSURE THAT ASSOCIATES RECOGNIZE THESE ITEMS ARE SUBJECT TO SPECIFIC PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS. MORE STRINGENT AUDITING REQUIREMENTS HAVE BEEN PUT IN PLACE TO REQUIRE ASSOCIATES AND MANAGEMENT TO PREPARE PACKAGES AND LABEL THEM ACCORDING TO DOT REGULATIONS.

column168: On August 28, 2019, at 1119 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XSL experienced a release of UN3139 Micronic 447RP from a 55 gallon poly drum to the dock floor. XPO personnel requested a contractor due to the hazardous state and the waste container needed to clean the spill. At 1410 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 3 gallons of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the dock floor. Contractors solidified the product and containerized the waste into a 55 gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was then over packed into a 95 gallon poly drum. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 08/05/2019 WE HAD AN AIRCRAFT (N625CK) STATIONED AT BEAGLE AIR FIELD LOCATED AT 15231 JONES RD IN WHITE CITY, OR. WE WERE ON A CONTRACT WITH THE OREGON DEPT. OF FORESTRY AND WERE FIGHTING A LOCAL FOREST FIRE IN THE AREA. WE ARE A HEAVY LIFT, LOGGING AND FIREFIGHTING HELICOPTER COMPANY. THE FUEL TRUCK AND TRAILER IN QUESTION WAS ASSIGNED TO THE AIRCRAFT ON THAT FIRE. WE WERE RELEASED FROM THE FIRE AT THE END OF THE SHIFT THAT SAME DAY (1930 HRS) AND THE AIRCRAFT AND SUPPORT VEHICLES WERE GOING TO RETURN TO OUR HOME BASE, LESS THAN TEN MILES AWAY. THE PICKUP AND SERVICE VAN HEADED OUT FOLLOWED BY THE FUEL TRUCK TRAILER. THE ROAD WAS A TWO LANE COUNTRY ROAD WITH SOME TIGHT CORNERS BUT OTHERWISE IN GOOD SHAPE. THE WEATHER WAS CLEAR AND DRY AND THERE WAS STILL PLENTY OF DAYLIGHT WHEN THEY LEFT THE ASSIGNMENT.   THE SERVICE VAN AND PICKUP GOT TO THE HANGAR AND THEY WAITED FOR APPROXIMATELY TWENTY MINUTES FOR THE FUEL TRUCK TO ARRIVE. WHEN HE DID NOT SHOW, THEY WENT BACK UP THE ROAD TO LOOK FOR HIM. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE AMBULANCE WAS LOADING THE DRIVER, WHO SELF EXTRICATED FROM THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE, AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE. THEY THEN CALLED ME AND I RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE SAFETY DIRECTOR WAS ALREADY THERE AND THE PRESIDENT OF THE COMPANY WAS EN-ROUTE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS PUTTING OUT ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND BOOMS TO TRY AND CONTAIN THE FUEL TO THE BEST OF THEIR ABILITY. THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED, DUE TO THE FACT THAT THEY WERE WORRIED ABOUT EXPLOSION AND MITIGATION OF THE LARGE AMOUNT OF JET FUEL BEING SPILLED.  FIRE I/C WOULD NOT ALLOW ANYONE TO GET NEAR THE VEHICLE UNTIL HAZMAT ARRIVED. (CONT. ON ADDITIONAL SHEET)
column169: WE HAVE SINCE CREATED ADDITIONAL POLICIES AND PUT IN PLACE REQUIREMENTS OF THE DRIVERS OF THESE TYPES OF TRUCKS. THEY INCLUDE ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON WEIGHT DISTRIBUTION BETWEEN TRUCK AND TRAILER, ADDITIONAL AND MORE STRINGENT PENALTIES FOR EXCESSIVE SPEED AND A MORE ROBUST DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM BEFORE THE DRIVER IS ALLOWED TO GO INTO THE FIELD. WE HAVE AMENDED THE "CROMAN CORP FLEET SAFETY PROGRAM" TO REFLECT THESE CHANGES AND REQUIRE DOCUMENTATION AND 100% SUCCESSFUL COMPLETION OF THE TRAINING PROGRAM BEFORE THE DRIVER MAY DRIVE ANY CROMAN CORP VEHICLE.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc arrived at shipper's location to pick up a load of drums.  As the driver was checking his load and preparing the enclosed cargo are for the next load of drums, the driver noticed a damp spot on the floor of his trailer.   Driver immediately located the drum, placed it on its side and began to clean approximately 3 liquid ounces of material on the floor.  No spilled material left the floor of the truck. Driver proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition,  all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured onto the trailer.    Now the driver was able to begin loading the drums from the current shipper's location.  It was  while the driver was placing the drums on his truck that he identified a drum that had a small  amount of rust at the bottom of the drum.  As the driver was placing this drum on its side a small amount of material escaped.  Driver contacted his manager so as to report the leak(s) and request a salvage drum be brought to his location.  The compromised drum was placed into the salvage drum as well as the clean-up debris.  Once complete, the container was secured and placed onto the trailer for continued  transportation.
column169: At the time the first container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of  leaking was  observed. Driver did state he saw a very small amount of rust toward the bottom of the drum.   Driver was reminded that where there is rust, even the smallest amount, there is typically  compromised metal. Drivers will continue to inspect each container before it is loaded and will take all appropriate  actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.  Which includes  overpacking or refusal of drums if rusted or structure seems compromised. Driver has been retrained in container inspection.   IN addition, the shippers have been advised of  the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

The compromised drum was placed into the salvage drum as well as the clean-up debris.  Once complete, the container was secured and placed onto the trailer for continued  transportation.
column169: At the time the first container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of  leaking was  observed. Driver did state he saw a very small amount of rust toward the bottom of the drum.   Driver was reminded that where there is rust, even the smallest amount, there is typically  compromised metal. Drivers will continue to inspect each container before it is loaded and will take all appropriate  actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.  Which includes  overpacking or refusal of drums if rusted or structure seems compromised. Driver has been retrained in container inspection.   IN addition, the shippers have been advised of  the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: On Friday, August 30, 2019 at approximately 10:25am, Airgas Houston, TX (Knight Road) Driver Alfonzo Martin was driving his assigned truck (Airgas Box Truck #303932) on Highway 290 West near address 17930 Northwest Fwy, Houston, TX 77065 in lane 5 of the six (6) lane highway (second from right).  The driver of a Dodge Ram 2500 truck was traveling in lane 2 (second from the left) and the truck collided with another vehicle (Kia Optima sedan) at a high rate of speed also in lane 2. The collision forced the Kia Optima into the left concrete barrier and the Dodge Ram Truck to dart across lanes and sideswipe the Airgas Truck driven by Driver Martin.  The collision forced the Airgas Truck to fishtail eventually causing the truck to overturn onto its right side (driver’s side) sliding on the pavement and colliding with the far right concrete barrier causing a hole in the barrier.  Several cylinders that were secured by straps inside the truck were ejected from the Airgas Box Truck due to the top of the truck opening. A few cylinders valves were damaged, however there was no release of product from any of the cylinders.   There was a release of diesel fuel, hydraulic fuel and DEF from the truck that was cleaned up by a 3rd party environmental company.

column168: ON 8/28/2019 AT 3:35 PM, A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY TRAIN CREW REPORTED THAT GATX 63607, A LOADED TANK CAR CONTAINING UN2491, CLASS 8, ETHANOLAMINE, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR IN THE KCS PORT ARTHUR, TX RAIL YARD. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE  THE RAIL CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND TWO OF SIX MANWAY SWING BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE RESPONDER SECURED ONE BOLT TOOL TIGHT BY TURNING THE NUT FOUR TIMES BY HAND AND THREE TIMES BY WRENCH. THE NUT ON THE OTHER BOLT WAS TURNED ONE TIME BY HAND AND THREE TIMES BY WRENCH. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REMEDIATED THE SPILLED LADING ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE RAIL CAR. ONCE COMPLETE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIL OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCTED A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. column168: On 08/05/2019 at 13:49 a driver for Chemical Waste Management, Inc- Transportation reported a spill at the 10-day storage area at 7170 John Brannon Rd. Sulphur, LA. Management was notified immediately upon discovery and responded to the on-property location of the spill. It was discovered that the Dewatering Vacuum box that had been transported had a front side wall failure next to the cable hook on the box. This box had been inspected by the driver before departing the offeror facility and no failure could be detected at the time. The truck route was retraced from 7170 John Brannon Rd to the offeror facility and it was found that leaked material had come in contact with the roadway in between the two locations. A preliminary investigation determined that the type of material offered, was not the material listed on the manifest. This material degraded the front side wall of the box, which during transport, caused the wall near the cable hook to fail. The emergency response plan was enacted, and the emergency response coordinator made emergency notifications. The emergency response contractors were contacted and began cleanup of the affected areas. In the course of this response, lines of communication and cooperation were kept open with local and governmental stakeholders.

column168: At 1956 ET, ERTS was notified by Andy Christenson with PAM Transport regarding a cargo release. All waste was collected and containerized for pending disposal

column168: RESPONDED TO LEAKING BOX IN UNLOAD. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND BROUGHT PACKAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. BOX HAD NO MARKINGS ANYWHERE, JUST THE SHIPPING LABEL. BOX DOESN'T LOOK DENTED BUT LEAKING. OPEN BOX AND FOUND TWO DENTED 1 GALLON CANS SURROUNDED BY FOAM. ON THE CANS IT HAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT MARKINGS.

THE BOX WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE SORT > UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND THE REMAINS OF BROKEN GLASS BOTTLE AND TWO INTACT ONE LITER BOTTLES. THE SHIPPER HAD STYROFOAM INSERTS FOR THE BOTTLES TO SIT IN. UNFORTUNATELY THOSE INSERTS MELTED AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL. AS SUCH IT IS A VIOLATION OF 49CFR WHEREIN THE PACKAGING COMPONENTS MUST BE IMPERVIOUS TO THE CHEMICALS BEING SHIPPED. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE OFFLOADING, AN OVERFILL OCCURRED, WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT WITHIN THE CIRCLE K PARKING LOT AND MIGRATED TO ADJACENT SOILS. THE POPE TRANSPORT COMPANY DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DEPLOYED HIS SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. THE AIKEN FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SOUTH CAROLINA DHEC RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. CIRCLE K PERSONNEL DISPATCHED FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL UTILIZED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE AFFECTED ASPHALT, AND HAND SHOVELED THE IMPACTED SOIL. NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUESTED. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: POPE TRANSPORT COMPANY WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column63: NA1993 DIESEL FUEL, 3, III DOT 406 HWY
column168: August 26, 2019 RB Stewart was delivering fuel to the Alvin Independent school District at Cardinal Dr., Alvin, TX. Once a location the RB Stewart driver connected all of the drop hoses and began filling the hose with fuel at that time the RB Stewart operator scene that the hose had a pinhole the operator immediately shut down the pump and put into reverse to assist and removing the remainder fuel that was left in the hose once that was completed they use poly polypropylene pads to assist in containing the fuel spill. Once that was done they contacted Masters Advance Remediation Services to assist in cleaning and removing the fuel from the parking lot and the storm drains.  1657 Masters Advance Remediation Services was contacted be Troy Mattix to assist RB Stewart and the fuel spill cleanup. 1730hrs.  Masters crew arrived on scene and the found fuel into the parking lot also reached a storm drain.  The foreman then placed a call to AAA flew pipe to assist them in cleaning the storm drain.  Masters crew applied clay absorbents, as Stardust to the parking lot to assist and removing the fuel from the hard service area.  Once AAA flex pipe arrived on scene, they began jetting pressure washing the storm drain to assist in removing the fuel. AAA flex pipes accumulated approximately 800 gallons of water and fuel or disposal.  Amount of waste generated.  1-55 gallon steel drum clay absorbent and diesel.  800 gallons of water and hydrocarbons.  The 800 gallons of waste was transported to liquid environmental solutions location 601 Gil Horn Houston Texas. The bill of lading number (149704)  1-55 gallon steel drum of waste was transported to WCA Fort Bend County landfill.  Manifest number (M-19-289-D001)
column169: WE PERFORM A VISUAL CHECK OF EACH HOSE AND NOW WILL ADD TO OUR TANK INSPECTION A PROCESS TO PRESSURE TEST HOSES EVERY YEAR.

column168: DRIVER WAS OFFLOADING AT THE CUSTOMER SITE. SPILL TOOK PLACE VIA THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON THE TANKER. DRIVER RECOGNIZED AFTER THE FACT THE DRAIN VALVE REMAINED CLOSED AFTER CONNECTING TO THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK WHILE ATTEMPTING TO OFFLOAD. IN ADDITION, THE PRESSURE REGULATOR ON THE TANK WAS SET HIGHER THAN THE NORMAL 20 PSI. THE SPILL WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN 0.5 GALLONS. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP PROPERLY BY THE  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY AND APPROVED BY THE CUSTOMER SAFETY REPRESENTATIVE ACKNOWLEDGING ADDITIONAL OUTSIDE CLEANUP EFFORTS WERE NOT REQUIRED.
column169: DRIVER WAS PUT THROUGH ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON HOW TO PROPERLY USE A REGULATOR AND UNLOAD. THE REGIONAL DRIVER TRAINER DID RIDE ALONG WITH THE DRIVER AFTER THE INCIDENT AND WENT OVER THE UNLOADING PROCESS AGAIN WITH THE DRIVER.

column168: WHEN AFTON CHEMICAL CORPORATION'S SAUGET  FACILITY  BEGAN UNLOADING PREPARATIONS FOR THE TANK CAR UTLX 950386, CONTAINING ISOBUTYLENE  (THE "TANK CAR"), THE UNLOADING OPERATOR DISCOVERED WHAT HE DESCRIBED AS AN "ICE BALL" IN THE SECONDARY CLOSURE ON THE UNLOADING LINE. FROM THE UNLOADERS EVALUATION, HE NOTED IT APPEARED THAT WHEN THE TANK CAR ARRIVED AT THE SAUGET FACILITY, THE UNLOADING VALVE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED, AND THE SECONDARY CLOSURE APPEARED TO HAVE ISOBUTYLENE LEAKING INTO THE CLOSURE FROM THE  UNLOADING VALVE. ONCE DISCOVERED, THE UNLOADING VALVE WAS SECURED, AND SECONDARY CLOSURE WAS FULLY CLOSED AND SECURED. BASED ON DOCUMENTATION PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER, ENTERPRISES PRODUCTS, THE TANK CAR ARRIVED AT THE SAUGET FACILITY WITH APPROXIMATELY 8,415 POUNDS LESS MATERIAL THAN WHEN TANK CAR WAS PLACED INTO COMMERCE BY THEM.

Explanation of Violation: During the transportation of the hazardous material, the driver was able to confirm the load securement on the rear portion of the trailer only, which the driver did confirm to the best of his ability per the federal regulatory requirements. However, the driver was not able to be present during the actual loading of the hazardous material, therefore the driver was unable to confirm the load securement to prevent forward movement and movement of the hazardous material from left to right. During this incident, the load appeared to shift forward, which was also due to improper securement from the shipper pertaining to the pallets used not being in sufficient condition for the hazardous material being transported, and improper load securement to prevent forward and left to right shifting.
column169: Corrective Actions: All drivers operating for Speed Freight, Inc. will have hazardous materials training conducted with CellEx Consulting Group. The training will include: - Identifying hazardous materials - Verifying proper securement of all freight including hazardous materials - Verifying that the hazardous materials are properly listed on bills of lading including emergency response information - Bills of lading with hazardous materials are in the proper locations during transport - Placarding and labeling requirements for hazardous materials - Defensive driving and extreme weather training - All drivers are trained on what to do in the event of a hazardous material incident. - All existing and new office personnel will be trained in hazardous materials and the proper procedures that are required to be followed when a hazardous material incident occurs to prevent reporting violations Upon completion of the hazardous materials training, each driver will be required to pass a written test with a score of 80% or higher. Each driver will also receive a certificate showing that the driver has completed the hazardous materials training required by the company.

column168: 49 CFR § 171.15 – Failure to provide immediate telephone/online notification of a reportable hazardous materials incident reportable under section 171.15(b).  Explanation of Violation:  During the transportation of the hazardous material, the driver was able to confirm the load securement on the rear portion of the trailer only, which the driver did confirm to the best of his ability per the federal regulatory requirements.  However, the driver was not able to be present during the actual loading of the hazardous material, therefore the driver was unable to confirm the load securement to prevent forward movement and movement of the hazardous material from left to right.   During this incident, the load appeared to shift forward, which was also due to improper securement from the shipper pertaining to the pallets used not being in sufficient condition for the hazardous material being transported, and improper load securement to prevent forward and left to right shifting.  Per 49 CFR § 177.834(a) – Packages secured in a motor vehicle.  Any package containing any hazardous material, not permanently attached to a motor vehicle, must be secured against shifting, including relative motion between packages, within the vehicle on which it is being transported, under conditions normally incident to transportation.  Packages having valves or other fittings must be loaded in a manner to minimize the likelihood of damage during transportation.  In the case of the transportation of this hazardous material, the driver/carrier confirmed the load securement of the hazardous material for the rear portion of the hazardous material prior to the seal being placed on the trailer.  However, confirming all aspects of load securement from shifting forward or left to right was not possible for the driver/carrier prior to the seal being placed on the trailer, due to the driver not being able to be present during the loading process.  In this case it was necessary for the driver/carrier to rely on the shipper for proper load securement in the areas where the driver/carrier were not able to confirm load securement per 49 CFR § 392.9.  49 CFR § 171.16 – Failure to file a written hazardous material incident report within 30 days of discovering a hazardous material incident reportable under section 171.15(b) or 171.16(a).  Explanation of Violation:  Based on the violations for the forward and left to right securement of the hazardous material and the improper palletization of the hazardous material, which was the responsibility of the shipper at the time of loading, and listed in the “Explanation of Violations” for 171.15, it is still the responsibility of the carrier to confirm that proper load securement is adhering to the proper regulatory requirements.  It is also the responsibility of the carrier to inform PHMSA of the hazardous materials incident within thirty days of the incident occurring.
column169: Corrective Actions:  Speed Freight, Inc. has corrected the violation for 171.16 by submitting the required notice to PHMSA, as should have been done within thirty days of the hazardous material incident. In addition to the training already received by all drivers and office personnel, the entire staff for Speed Freight, Inc. will be retrained in hazardous materials which will be conducted with CellEx Consulting Group.  The training will include:  - Identifying hazardous materials - Verifying proper securement of all freight including hazardous materials - Verifying that the hazardous materials are properly listed on bills of lading including emergency response information - Bills of lading with hazardous materials are in the proper locations during transport - Placarding and labeling requirements for hazardous materials - Defensive driving and extreme weather training  - All drivers are trained on what to do in the event of a hazardous material incident.   - All existing and new office personnel will be trained in hazardous materials and the proper procedures that are required to be followed when a hazardous material incident occurs to prevent reporting violations  Upon completion of the hazardous materials training, each driver will be required to pass a written test with a score of 80% or higher.  Each driver will also receive a certificate showing that the driver has completed the hazardous materials training required by the company.  By providing this training, the violations for 171.15 and 171.16 will be prevented from occurring in the future.
